          "content": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "Show that $8\\cos^4\\theta - 8\\cos^2\\theta + 1 - \\cos 4\\theta = 0$."
            }
          ],
          "marks": 2,
          "is_independent": true,
          "answer": {
            "option_label": null,
            "summary": "$8\\cos^4\\theta - 8\\cos^2\\theta + 1 - \\cos 4\\theta = 0$ using double angle identities.",
            "content": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Use double angle identity for $\\cos 4\\theta = 2\\cos^2 2\\theta - 1 = 8\\cos^4\\theta - 8\\cos^2\\theta + 1$. Thus, $8\\cos^4\\theta - 8\\cos^2\\theta + 1 - \\cos 4\\theta = 0$."
              }
            ],
            "alternatives": null
          }
        },
        {
          "label": "b",
          "stimulus": null,
          "content": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "Let $x = \\cos \\theta$ in the equation $16x^4 - 16x^2 + 2 - \\sqrt{2} = 0$, show that $\\cos 4\\theta = \\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2}$."
            }
          ],
          "marks": 2,
          "is_independent": false,
          "answer": {
            "option_label": null,
            "summary": "$\\cos 4\\theta = \\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2}$",
            "content": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Substitute $x = \\cos \\theta$ into the equation and use the result from part (a) to get $2(8\\cos^4\\theta - 8\\cos^2\\theta + 1) - \\sqrt{2} = 0$. Thus, $2\\cos 4\\theta - \\sqrt{2} = 0$ or $\\cos 4\\theta = \\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2}$."
              }
            ],
            "alternatives": null
          }
